[LEGAL REVIEW REQUIRED] Simplified CDD (SDD) is not available in all jurisdictions. Under UAE AML Law and ADGM AML Rules, SDD is only available for specific prescribed low-risk categories and requires documented internal risk assessment. DIFC DFSA does not permit SDD as a default. KSA SAMA does not recognise SDD as a formal risk reduction category for most financial institutions. Any SDD configuration must be approved by the tenant's MLRO and legal counsel before activation.
 
2.4 Manual Review, Escalation, and Rejection Flow
When auto-approval criteria are not met, or where screening hits, EDD flags, or analyst discretion require human review, the following escalation flow applies.
 
1. Case auto-created
M-10 creates a case record with full customer data package, risk score, screening results, and document inventory attached.
2. Queue assignment
Case assigned to appropriate queue (Standard Review / EDD Review / Sanctions Review / Senior Escalation) based on risk band and trigger type.
3. Analyst review
Analyst opens case. Reviews all data, documents, screening hits, and risk factors. Can: Request Additional Information (RAI), Escalate, Approve, or Reject.
4. Request Additional Information
System sends configured request to customer. Case status moves to Pending Customer Response. SLA paused. Timer set for customer response window.
5. MLRO escalation
High-risk or unacceptable-risk cases, PEP true matches, complex structures, or analyst uncertainty trigger MLRO queue. MLRO reviews and decides.
6. SAR consideration
Where suspicion arises during review, MLRO assesses STR/SAR obligation. If filed, case status updated (masked to operational staff per tipping-off rules). Onboarding may proceed or be declined.
7. Senior Management sign-off
For EDD approvals and PEP onboarding, separate senior management approval captured in M-11 with timestamped record.
8. Rejection
Rejection decision recorded with reason code. Customer notified with appropriately worded message (tipping-off-compliant). Case locked and archived.
9. Audit trail closed
All steps, decisions, timestamps, and actor IDs written immutably to M-12 audit log.
 
2.5 Ongoing Re-KYC and Trigger-Based Review
Periodic refresh — scheduled
M-14 triggers a re-KYC workflow based on the customer's risk-band review period. Customer receives request for document refresh or declaration update.
Event-triggered refresh
System monitors for: document expiry, UBO/director change alerts from registry API, adverse media monitoring hits, transaction anomaly flags, customer-reported changes.
Change-event workflow
On trigger: risk score recalculated. If risk band increases, EDD workflow initiated. If risk band decreases, standard refresh applied.
Exit / off-boarding
If customer cannot satisfy re-KYC requirements or risk becomes unacceptable, exit workflow initiated. Records retained per retention schedule. SAR obligation assessed.
 
