SECTION 05
Technical and Infrastructure Requirements
 
5.1 Architecture Principles
Multi-tenancy
Full logical isolation between tenants. Separate encryption keys per tenant. No shared data spaces. Tenant ID stamped on all records. API keys scoped to tenant.
API-first
Every platform function is exposed via versioned REST API before any UI is built on top. External integrations and white-label deployments consume the same API surface.
Event-driven core
All cross-module communication via an internal event bus (Kafka or equivalent). Modules publish domain events and subscribe to events they need. No direct inter-module database calls.
Stateless services
All application services are horizontally scalable and stateless. State lives in the data layer. Session state in Redis with configurable TTL.
Zero-trust network
Service-to-service authentication via mutual TLS and short-lived JWT tokens. No implicit trust within the perimeter.
Immutable audit core
The audit trail service is write-only via API. No service has direct database write access to the audit table. Admin cannot delete audit records through any UI surface.
Privacy by design
PII is classified at field level before storage. Encryption, masking, and minimisation decisions are made at schema design time, not as post-hoc additions.
Data residency compliance
Storage backend must support region-pinned data placement. UAE customer data: UAE region. KSA customer data: KSA region (mandatory under KSA PDPL). Cross-border transfer controls enforced at API gateway.
 
