5.5 Audit Logging and Tamper Resistance
The audit trail is the regulatory and legal backbone of the platform. Its integrity is non-negotiable. The following design patterns must be implemented.
 
Append-only write model
The audit log table has no UPDATE or DELETE permissions granted to any application service identity. Only an INSERT-only service account can write. Deletion is physically impossible during retention period.
Hash chaining
Each audit record includes the SHA-256 hash of the previous record in the same tenant partition. Modification of any historic record breaks the chain and is detectable.
Immutable object storage backup
Daily export to S3 with Object Lock (WORM mode) enabled. Retention period matched to regulatory requirement. Tamper detection via hash verification on restore.
Timestamp integrity
All timestamps from authoritative NTP source. UTC standard. Timestamps are set by the audit service, not by the calling service — prevents manipulation.
Admin action logging
All M-15 configuration changes are written to the audit trail with before/after state. Platform super-admin actions are logged to a separate, immutable cross-tenant audit log.
Regulatory export
Audit trail can be exported as signed, structured PDF or JSON-L report for regulator submission. Export event itself is logged.
 
5.6 Rules Engine Design
The rules engine evaluates business logic at workflow decision nodes. Rules are authored in M-15 by admin users with no code required. The engine evaluates rules in the following order: structural rules (mandatory) → jurisdiction rules → tenant-specific rules → product rules.
 
Rule types supported
Conditional (if/then/else), threshold-based, list membership, date/time based, score-range based, multi-condition AND/OR/NOT.
Rule inputs
Any field collected in any module, system-generated risk scores, screening results, document statuses, computed values, and external API responses.
Rule outputs
Workflow routing decision, field requirement change, document requirement change, notification trigger, case escalation trigger, risk score adjustment.
Rule conflict resolution
Priority ordering per rule set. Higher specificity (product + entity + jurisdiction) overrides lower specificity (tenant default). Conflict logging to audit trail.
Rule version control
Every change to a rule set creates a new version. Historic rule versions retained. Rules applied at onboarding are locked to the version in effect at that time.
Testing
Sandbox mode allows rule evaluation against test data sets before production deployment. Test results saved and reviewable.
 

